<div id="review_127857319" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/127857319" />
    <a title="Harvey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3324623-harvey"><img alt="Harvey" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/127857319?book_show_action=true">Oct 25, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Harvey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Harvey" href="/user/show/3324623-harvey">Harvey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer127857319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10221755026443740119">I had previously read, and loved, Ms. Stanley&apos;s City of Dragons, a murder mystery very atmospherically set in San Francisco&apos;s Chinatown, circa 1940. <br/><br/>So I was curious about this one and glad I gave it a try. She calls the style &quot;Roman Noir&quot; and I&apos;m not so sure that applies. But it does cover &quot;palace intrigue&quot; of the Roman Governor of London/Brittania as the Governor&apos;s medical doctor, friend, and &quot;fixer&quot; solves murders and a political plot.<br/><br/>Stanley is a Classics scholar so knows her Roman stuff. I </span>
  <span id="freeText10221755026443740119" style="display:none">I had previously read, and loved, Ms. Stanley's City of Dragons, a murder mystery very atmospherically set in San Francisco's Chinatown, circa 1940. <br /><br />So I was curious about this one and glad I gave it a try. She calls the style "Roman Noir" and I'm not so sure that applies. But it does cover "palace intrigue" of the Roman Governor of London/Brittania as the Governor's medical doctor, friend, and "fixer" solves murders and a political plot.<br /><br />Stanley is a Classics scholar so knows her Roman stuff. I liked how she described life in London during the time, including an interesting take on slavery and class; plus the doctor's use of herbs, etc.<br /><br />This is the first in what Stanley plans as a series and I will look for the next one. (Alyhough I will look forward to the next in the Chinatown series more.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="10221755026443740119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


